post_text:
Rick and Kona Ice of St. Augustine are helping our local schools raise money... one shaved ice at a time. 🍧

Since August 2016, the Kona Ice truck has raised almost $40,000 for Putnam County schools.

The fundraising process begins when students bring money to school to pay for a Kona shaved ice. Then, a percent of sales go back to the school.

Our students and teachers absolutely love having the Kona Ice truck pull up to the school! It was certainly a hit today at the District office!

Thank you Rick and Kona Ice of St. Augustine for your support of our schools and our community! #ProudtobePCSD

On Wednesdays, Kelley Smith does STEM!

Mrs. Jill Ashford’s class had to build a structure with random materials that were chosen blindly.

Mrs. Leslie Cooper’s class got to see the effect water has on Skittles.

5th graders in STEM Lab were creating postcards to send to space. Yes that’s right...Space Mail! These postcards will travel to space and then get mailed back to the students so that they will have their own artifact from space.

#ProudtobePCSD
shared_text:
Kelley Smith is with Mike Tucker and 3 others.
September 3 at 9:15 PM ·

Yesterday was STEM day in the classroom at KSES. These occur on Wednesdays each week and basically this is when each teacher gets to have the fun of teaching STEM to their students. Check out some of the cool things your children did with their teachers yesterday....

Mrs. Jill Ashford’s class had to build a structure with random materials that were chosen blindly.

Mrs. Leslie Cooper’s class got to see the effect water has on Skittles.

5th graders in STEM Lab were creating postcards to send to space. Yes that’s right...Space Mail! These post cards will travel to space and then get mailed back to the students so that they will have their own artifact from space. They have learned some interesting things this week about traveling to space and how you sleep, exercise, the food preparation, brushing your teeth, and using the outhouse.

Please join us tomorrow, September 4th for a PCSD Friday Family Learning Byte! In the session, "Connecting with Canvas: Becoming a Parent Observer", we will provide an overview of the Canvas LMS, walk parents through linking to their student's Canvas account, and share some of the most helpful features for keeping up with assignments and due dates.

Please register for this event using this link: bit.ly/PCSDCanvas

There are 4 repeating sessions throughout the day. Each session can hold up to 100 participants.

Times are as follows:
8:00AM - 8:45AM
9:00AM - 9:45AM
11:30AM - 12:15PM
2:30PM - 3:15PM

On September 11th, we will host Cultivating the Joy of Reading sessions throughout the day for our families. These repeating sessions will focus on ways to encourage and promote independent reading at home. We will also introduce myOn and AR to families. Stay tuned for more details.

#ProudtobePCSD

post_text:
Florida is the leader in the global space industry, and we want to cultivate our students today to help create and build the space economy of tomorrow. To that end, we are participating in a statewide initiative – Dream Big Florida – that will help spark our students to visualize the future of life in space to benefit Earth.

Through this Florida STEM program, organized by Northeast Florida Regional STEM2 Hub, the Florida Consortia of Education Foundations, and Club for the Future (Blue Origin’s non-profit), we are asking every student in our district to create a postcard answering the question, “Why do you think Earth needs space?” These postcards will be flown to space and back on upcoming launches of Blue Origin’s New Shepard reusable rocket and will then be mailed back to each student with a ‘Flown to Space’ postmark.

Our Superintendent makes an appearance in the 'Dream Big Florida' video featured below!:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=icJsOGavcLI

#ProudtobePCSD
#DreambigFlorida

post_text:
Amazing achievement Melrose Elementary School!!

“Time to celebrate! Our school has recently been recognized for our work implementing a school-wide Positive Behavior Interventions and Support (PBIS) framework. PBIS is a set of strategies based in behavioral and biomedical science that enhances student quality of life and reduces problem behaviors. National research shows that full implementation of this framework leads to improved student outcomes. By establishing this framework, we are developing student skills, making changes to the school environment, acknowledging appropriate student behavior, and using data to identify needed supports for our students. As a result of this work, we are being recognized by the FLPBIS Project for achieving Gold PBIS Model School status. This award demonstrates our commitment to positive and equitable outcomes for all students and helps us celebrate our efforts as we progress toward full implementation of PBIS. To learn more about the FLPBIS Project’s Model School program, visit www.flpbis.org”

#ProudtobePCSD

SUCH AN IMPORTANT MESSAGE!

As we approach the start of school we wanted to remind our parents, students, and staff that sick students and adults should remain home.

Screening for the following symptoms is recommended at the beginning of every school day for each student, teacher, and staff member prior to entering school facilities

· Temperature (100.4) or higher

· Sore throat

· New uncontrolled cough that causes difficulty breathing

· Diarrhea, Vomiting, or Abdominal Pain

· New onset of severe headache

· Loss of taste and/or smell

If you think you may have COVID-19 or have questions, please contact:

Putnam County COVID-19 Hotline at (386) 329-1904

#COVIDStopsWithMe

#ProudtobePCSD

post_text:
Middleton-Burney Elementary School a historic first day! We know your little raiders are going to have a fantastic year!

#ProudtobePCSD
shared_text:
Middleton-Burney Elementary School
August 24 at 7:17 PM ·

We feel so grateful to be a learning community that cares so much!

Thank you to the parents who trusted us with your children today. They arrived masked, well-mannered, and ready to learn!

Thank you to the parents that chose the virtual option. You made it easier for us to explore education in this brand new climate. You also logged in, and expressed patience and grace as we work out the technical kinks.

Most of all... thank you to our teachers and staff!!! You laid down your anxieties and marched fearlessly into your classrooms, whether virtual or in-person, media center or math. You gave your all. You worked HARD to make this a smooth opening. You practiced safely. You operated with professionalism and LOVE!

Every member of this family is valuable. Thank you for an historic first day!

Great job CL Overturf, Jr 6th Grade Center!

"Thank you to all our parents who sent their children today! You are trusting us to be safe so I wanted to give you a glimpse into our classrooms. CLO's first day is going great. Yes, it looks a little different in the classrooms and hallways, but the students are being so understanding and cooperative. Kudos to our teachers for making their rooms inviting in spite of the barriers. Special thank you to Andrew Moss, David Gehrsitz and Jesse Crews for spending all weekend finishing the pods in the classrooms and barriers for their colleagues. Thank you for keeping us safe!"

post_text:
"Today was a day of celebrating victory over circumstances! We pulled together as a team to serve and welcome a sector of society that shapes our future. We know education is powerful but the title of teaching is divine. Each teacher sows seeds of encouragement, love, faith, hope, strength and so much more! How, you may ask? They only BELIEVE! And when someone believes in you, it’s hard not to believe in yourself!

We would like to thank the ladies of Trinity United Methodist Church for the amazing breakfast and goodie bag! We also would like to thank LSI for providing breakfast snacks and beverages.

A very special thanks to Amber Symonds, Alice MacGibbon Keith, Kristin White, Alyssa Barnes, Ryan Davis, Shelby Bellamy, Brandi Majesky, Travis Gilyard and Brian Keith for participating in one of the highest honors: serving!

I believe 👏🏾👏🏾 in you!"

#ProudtobePCSD

Parents: Sudden changes in routine, as well as being home all the time can be hard for children.

Signs of stress include:

Excessive worry or sadness
Unhealthy sleeping or eating habits
Difficulty with attention and concentration

Get tips for talking with your child about coronavirus: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/talking-with-children.html

Reading Rock Stars at Kelley Smith Elementary School 📚

"After being selected as one of the winners for the WJXT4 The Local Station / News4JAX/Douglas Law Firm National Reading Awareness Month campaign, our visit with Richard Nunn was unfortunately cancelled due to COVID. Total bummer, but I got together with them and they were able to make our class a video congratulating them and wishing them good luck in their next school year. They went above and beyond, and I’m so grateful to both News4Jax and Douglas Law Firm for supporting reading in our communities! 📚

Thank you to Jennifer Waugh, Melanie Lawson, Bruce Hamilton, and Richard Nunn for your encouraging words to this deserving group of students who I am missing so much!! ❤️

Also, huge shoutout to marketing director, Kelly Goddard, and executive producer, Tom Swider, for working behind the scenes and turning this idea into a reality! ✨" - Mrs. Alexis M Lewis

Today, Board Members, District Administrators, School Principals, other PCSD Staff & Dept of Health team members attended a workshop facilitated by Supt Surrency and PCSD Leadership Team to discuss school reopening . The decision has been made for the first day of school to be pushed back to August 24, 2020. 10-month staff will return August 17, 2020. To find out more, be sure to look at the details outlined in the board workshop when it is posted on the Putnam County School's webpage and YouTube tomorrow.
If your a parent and have further questions, please contact your child's school.
If you are employee, please contact your school principal or director.

post_text:
This afternoon Superintendent Rick Surrency led a virtual discussion on ‘Implementing an Equitable Approach to Increase Graduation Rates’ to a group of Superintendents from across the nation.

What an honor to have School Districts from all over the United States look to Putnam County as a role model in Graduation Rate improvement.

In 2015, PCSD’s graduation rate was an astonishing 54.9%. Since implementing our Graduation Initiative, putting in place systems of support, and by increasing awareness around timely graduation, we saw drastic improvements to our graduation rate beginning in 2016. We proudly boasted an 86.3% graduation rate in 2019. Our target goal for 2020 is 90%.

As we look toward the future, we are optimistic that our District staff, students, and parents will continue striving for excellence by setting high expectations in student performance, and graduation rates.

#ProudtobePCSD

***Due to the circumstances we are asking that you keep your appointment. If you can not make one of these days and times we are scheduling zoom conferences with students as well.

If you should have any other questions or need additional information please contact our office.

May 30 at 11:00 AM ·

Watch history unfold on Saturday, May 30, as NASA and SpaceX launch astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley to the International Space Station. This mission marks the first time since the retirement of the space shuttle in 2011 that humans will fly to the space station from U.S. soil. The first launch attempt on May 27 was scrubbed due to weather.

Set a reminder to tune for joint NASA/SpaceX coverage starting at 11 a.m. EDT, with liftoff currently targeted for 3:22 p.m. EDT. 🚀

post_text:
“Today I got to meet with and present proclamations to some incredible Putnam County residents that lift up everyone around them.

Brian Bunch is a 5th Grade student at Interlachen Elementary. Brian, along with his sister, saved money and bought a 3D printer to make face clips for the masks of our frontline COVID-19 responders to relieve ear pressure and irritation.

Brian Parrish, a food service manager and robotics coach at Ochwilla Elementary School, created mask adjusters to make masks larger for adults or smaller for special needs children. Together, the Brians printed and distributed 900 masks to Shands, University of Florida College of Dentistry, Azalea Health, and more.

Battalion Chief Steve Dennis worked alongside Chief Quin Romay to start the Putnam County Fire Rescue. It was an honor to thank Chief Dennis for 45 years of dedicated service to Putnam County and our fellow Floridians.”

#ProudtobePCSD

Brian Bunch, a student at IES, also received a proclamation for printing extenders. Thank you to both for helping those on the front lines of this pandemic.

Pictured are Superintendent Dr. Rick Surrency, Assistant Principal Sharice Williams, Principal Beth Leary, Brian Parrish, Brian Bunch, Grace Bunch and Senator Perry.

This afternoon, Q.I. Roberts Jr-Sr High School welcomed seniors on campus to drive through and pick up their caps, gowns, and other regalia.

They had a great turn out with family members, students, faculty and staff there to cheer on the graduating class of 2020! 🎓

Students were welcomed at the road by custodial staff who cheered them on and even got the passing cars to participate, honking their horns as they drove past.

Students then dropped of books and chrome books, picked up their senior class alumni shirts, and then received their caps and gowns from their principal, Joe Theobold. 🎓 🎉

#ProudtobePCSD

“ADK would like to congratulate Colby Mikell from Palatka High School on being chosen as the 2019-2020 recipient of our High School Senior Scholarship. Colby was chosen based on his academic achievements as well as his extensive school and community involvement. He has been involved in Football, Soccer, Weightlifting, and Musical Theatre. Along with these commitments, he still found time to become an Eagle Scout and serve on student council for 4 years, 2 years in a row as class president. Colby plans to attend Belmont University in Tennessee to pursue a degree in Music Business. Congratulations to Colby and his family! The sisters of ADK will be looking for great things from you in the future!”

Ask him at 17 if he wanted to go fishing, not only would he go, but he'd want to compete with you on how big your catch was compared to his most likely.

post_text:
It is a pleasure to announce that Brandon “Tony” Benford has been named the principal of William D. Moseley Elementary School for the 2020-2021 school year.

Mr. Benford, who has been the Assistant Principal at Moseley and was the Putnam County School District’s 2019 Assistant Principal of the Year, will be taking the place of Sarajean McDaniel. We are excited for the momentum that has been built at Moseley over the last three years to continue under Mr. Benford’s leadership.

In 2017, Mr. Benford enthusiastically accepted the challenge of helping lead the turnaround effort at Moseley Elementary School. His focus on changing the school’s culture has been a driving force in transforming the school and the entire community.

Mr. Benford has strength as an honest communicator who develops trust with all who work with him. He builds relationships with all stakeholders, especially parents. He is a mentor to students at risk and an advocate who helps students believe in themselves.

Please join us in welcoming Mr. Benford to this new role! 🎉

#ProudtobePCSD
text:
It is a pleasure to announce that Brandon “Tony” Benford has been named the principal of William D. Moseley Elementary School for the 2020-2021 school year.

Mr. Benford, who has been the Assistant Principal at Moseley and was the Putnam County School District’s 2019 Assistant Principal of the Year, will be taking the place of Sarajean McDaniel. We are excited for the momentum that has been built at Moseley over the last three years to continue under Mr. Benford’s leadership.

In 2017, Mr. Benford enthusiastically accepted the challenge of helping lead the turnaround effort at Moseley Elementary School. His focus on changing the school’s culture has been a driving force in transforming the school and the entire community.

Mr. Benford has strength as an honest communicator who develops trust with all who work with him. He builds relationships with all stakeholders, especially parents. He is a mentor to students at risk and an advocate who helps students believe in themselves.

Please join us in welcoming Mr. Benford to this new role! 🎉

#ProudtobePCSD

post_text:
McDaniel named Florida Principal of the Year

Sarajean McDaniel was selected Saturday as the 2020 Florida Principal of the Year by the state Department of Education.
McDaniel was recognized for her role in improvements made at Moseley Elementary School in Palatka. The school was removed from the state's turnaround list in 2019 when it improved to a C rating.
Putnam County School Superintendent Rick Surrency said McDaniel "exemplifies excellence in educational leadership."
"This is a great day for Putnam County," Surrency said.
McDaniel was recently promoted to the school district office to serve as a leadership development coach.
For more, visit https://www.palatkadailynews.com/mcdaniel-named-florida-principal-year.

PCSD TUESDAY TIP:

Get Plenty of Exercise!

Exercise helps us think better. When we move and groove, our problem-solving, memory, and attention improve. Physical activity is a natural way to reduce stress and prevent anxiety. Experts say that when we move and get our heart rate up, it has a positive impact on how we think.

Information regarding 'Online and Home Learning' can be found here: homelearning.putnamschools.org

-
#ProudtobePCSD #TipsTuesday

This week the Putnam County School District Administrative office had the sweetest visitors from Kelley Smith Elementary School!

Lunch was provided to the entire office and an uplifting yard sign was left in front of the building. The words on the sign could not be more true... We ARE #bettertogether.

Kelley Smith has been delivering signs and bags of goodies around our community to essential workers, essential businesses, and school administrators.

Thank you sharks for your thoughtfulness and for spreading joy at the District office and around our community. 💙🦈

post_text:
Interlachen High School seniors received yard signs congratulating them and recognizing them as the 'Class of 2020'.

Interlachen High School Principal, Bryan Helms, said, "The IHS Team wanted to do something special for our class of 2020. This class of 2020 really is missing a lot of activities as a senior class, this is just our way to still recognize the hard work they have accomplished during their high school careers. The signs were something that we are trying to help make people smile during this troubling time. We love our kids and wanted them to know that we are proud of them."

Plans are in the works for other PCSD high schools to do something similar.

We are so proud of the class of 2020! 🎉

#ProudtobePCSD

2020 PRODUCT OF PUTNAM

The '2020 Product of Putnam' award recognizes individuals who graduated from the Putnam County School District and have given back to the Putnam County community.

Times are difficult for many right now. Maybe you know of an individual helping those on the frontlines. Perhaps you know of an individual going above and beyond to lift the spirits of children in our community. These individuals would be perfect nominees for our 'Product of Putnam' award.

To nominate a candidate(s) please scan the QR Code OR follow the link below. Remember, you can submit more than one nominee!

We will recognize individuals that work in fields including, but not limited to, healthcare, education, law enforcement, welding, industrial manufacturing, volunteers, government, entrepreneurs, and agriculture.

https://bit.ly/2WEU5p5

Deadline to submit nominations is May 1st, 2020.

#ProudtobePCSD #ProductofPutnam #PositivelyPutnam

post_text:
Putnam County School District would like to formally thank the Northeast Florida Regional STEM2 Hub for the donation of 25 laptops for Putnam teachers delivering virtual instruction to students during the COVID epidemic.

The laptops come at an essential time for the district as the need for teachers to have a device is paramount. We cannot thank STEM2Hub enough for their generosity helping us tackle the digital divide that occurs in small, rural districts.

Our partnership with the STEM2Hub continues to be so essential. We are reminded during this time of the need for community and schools to join together in times of struggle. Thank you, thank you!

#ProudtobePCSD

post_text:
Are you currently employees with PCSD as a paraprofessional?

Do you work in a classroom setting on a regular basis?

Have you ever thought about becoming a teacher?

Do you have an AA degree or at least 60 college credit hours?

Have you ever wondered how you could earn a Bachelor’s Degree?

Are you ready to take the next step in your career?

If you answered yes to these questions, we have great news for you!

PCSD and St. Leo University have partnered to provide a way for this to happen – ‘Paras to Pros’.

We are excited to share all the details with you so that you can know for yourself how you can become a teacher for PCSD! Please make plans to join us (virtually) at the following

“Paras to Pros” Virtual Informational Session.

April 16th, 2020 – 2:30 PM

Contact Tonya Whitehurst, Director of Human Resources for a calendar invite.

We will start at the school and head through the neighborhood by the school at 5:00 first, then go through the parking lot of the ball fields by James A Long. Our next neighborhood will be the Bostwick area we should be at West River Road around 5:20ish and then go down Palmetto Bluff. The last stop will be Bardin. We should be there around 6:00. We are only going to be going right past Bardin Grocery, so if you live farther down than that, please make plans to come park at Bardin Grocery. Please share this with your neighbors so they are aware the traffic may get backed up during these times. Please share so we can see as many families as possible. We can't wait to see everyone!!

LUNCH DOODLES!

This sounds like a fun way for our students to get those creative juices flowing!

Thank you for the tip Putnam County Public Library System!
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
LUNCH DOODLES with Mo Willems! Episode 01

Putnam County Public Library System
April 1 at 9:21 AM ·

LUNCH DOODLES with Mo Willems!
Kennedy Center Education Artist-in-Residence at Home
Mo Willems invites YOU into his studio every day for his LUNCH DOODLE. Learners worldwide can draw, doodle and explore new ways of writing by visiting Mo’s studio virtually once a day for the next few weeks. Grab some paper and pencils, pens, or crayons and join Mo to explore ways of writing and making together. If you post your art to social media, be sure to hashtag it with #MoLunchDoodles!

New episodes will be posted each weekday at 1:00 p.m. ET and then remain online to be streamed afterwards. Check back each weekday for new LUNCH DOODLES!

And visit Kennedy Center@Home to enjoy free videos of extraordinary live and on-demand performances and educational activities to do at home, with new releases daily.

More info here: https://www.kennedy-center.org/education/mo-willems/

http://www.putnamschools.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=333201&pageId=13246870

For a list of Putnam County locations allowing students access to their WIFI networks. The list is continuously updating so be sure to come back to check if a location becomes available near you.

When going to any of these locations please remember to adhere to CDC Guidelines (No more than 10 people gathered together, with at least six feet of distance from one another). We ask that you pull up and access the WIFI while staying in your vehicle.

We are very thankful for the businesses that have provided this much needed service to our students.

If you are willing to help our students, please email info@my.putnamschools.org with your business name, your name, physical street address, WIFI name, and password or if open access.

Superintendent Dr. Rick Surrency is pleased to share with you that we will be expanding our meal services to students beginning March 30th, 2020 and will continue to provide this service for as long as 'Online and Home Learning' is in effect in Putnam County.

Breakfast and Lunch will be served from 10:00AM - 1:00PM. Meals will be prepackaged and distributed by drive-thru at select school parent pick-up/bus loops or pick-up at bus stops throughout the county to be consumed off site.

*Children must be present to receive their meal.

More information can be found by visiting:
http://www.putnamschools.org/homelearning/food_service_distribution

How canceled events and self-quarantines save lives, in one chart

Putnam County, FL BOCC
March 16 at 11:03 AM ·

This is an informative article which helps explain how social distancing, cancelled events and quarantines are a very valuable tool in a community's response to COVID-19.
These efforts ARE NOT about stopping the virus, THEY ARE about slowing its spread so that our medical infrastructure & medical community can better handle the demand. We have some AMAZING individuals who work in the medical field (physicians, nurses, therapist, technicians, etc.). They are looking at endless hours of work, away from their loved ones to support our community. WE CAN HELP THEM by taking some general precautions for a little while. Please SHARE the message, and do everything we can to support those working on the front lines.

https://www.vox.com/2020/3/10/21171481/coronavirus-us-cases-quarantine-cancellation

post_text:
The Putnam County School District has received information from the State of Florida indicating that Spring Break will be extended until at least April 15th, 2020.

The State of Florida has cancelled all standardized testing for the 2019/2020 school year.

The State has also cancelled school grades for the 2019/2020 school year.

The District Administrative team will be meeting tomorrow to provide an instructional plan for students that will take effect March 30th, this could involve online and other learning materials.

More information coming soon!

post_text: Pre-K will begin accepting applications for the 2020-2021 school year on Monday, March 2nd. Please visit the elementary school your child is zoned for to pick up an application folder. Before you can turn your application in, you must have a Certificate of Eligibility from the Office of Early Learning. Please visit: https://familyservices.floridaearlylearning.com/ to begin this process. You will also need your child's birth certificate and proof of residency. When you have all of that documentation, turn these back into the school you are zoned for. You can contact the Pre-K Office at 386-312-4906 with any questions.

Representatives from the Putnam County School District met today, February 28th, with officials from the Putnam County Health Department to determine steps for preventing the spread of the Coronavirus.

According to the Center for Disease Control, Putnam County is at a low risk for the spread of the virus currently. The Putnam County School District is asking our community to follow the CDC prevention guidelines that include:

* Everyone should always practice good personal health habits to help prevent flu.
* Stay home when you are sick. Remain home for at least 24 hours after you no longer have a fever or signs of a fever without the use of fever-reducing medicines.
* Cover your coughs and sneezes with a tissue.
*Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. Use at least a 60% alcohol-based hand sanitizer if soap and water are not available.
* Clean frequently touched surfaces and objects.

If you have any specific questions, please contact your child's school.

The 14 best spellers from North Florida competed live Thursday night for a spot in the Scripps National Spelling Bee.

Putnam County was represented by Armand Kuykendall, a 6th grader from Miller Middle School. This is the second year in a row that he has made it to First Coast Spelling Bee. We are so proud of Armand and know that his future is B-R-I-G-H-T!

Erik Williams, a 7th grade St. Johns County Day student is moving on to Washington D.C.

The winning word: Allergenic.

Good luck in the Scripps National Spelling Bee Erik!

#ProudtobePCSD

"The National African American Read-In is the nation’s first and oldest event dedicated to diversity in literature. It was established in 1990 by the Black Caucus of the National Council of Teachers of English to make literacy a significant part of Black History Month. This initiative has reached more than 6 million participants around the world. Today, Moseley Elementary School was honored to host our First Annual African American Read-In. We would like to thank all of the guest readers who joined us today at Moseley for this wonderful event!"

#ProudToBePCSD

Jenkins Middle School - Modified Lockdown

Feb. 11, 2020 - Jenkins Middle School is on a modified lockdown at this time. All students, faculty, and staff are safe.

Multiple deputies and school staff are on the scene. A firearm was found on campus and was secured.

This is an ongoing investigation, When more information becomes available it will be released. No students will be released early from Jenkins Middle School today.
